
# JLRS Matchup and Fixture Design

This document defines how players are paired, how often they play, and how “stretch matches” are integrated into the fixture system to maximize both competitive integrity and player development.

---

## Design Principles

1. **Every match should be purposeful** — no filler matches between mismatched players

2. **Players need both competitive and developmental matches** — winning 50% of the time is ideal for rating accuracy but not sufficient for growth

3. **Stretch matches are a coaching tool, not a rating exploit** — the Elo system already handles cross-tier matches correctly; fixture design just needs to create them deliberately

4. **Fixtures are generated per session, not per week** — matches happen during daily 2–3 hour academy training blocks where all players are present simultaneously

5. **The system must bootstrap itself** — during the provisional phase when most players are at 1000, the algorithm uses round-robin discovery before transitioning to rating-based pairing

---

## Match Types by Purpose

Every league match falls into one of three pairing categories:

| Category | Rating Gap | Purpose | Share of session fixtures |
|----------|------------|---------|---------------------------|
| **Competitive** | 0–100 points | True peer-level play. Tests current form. Produces the most reliable rating signal | 50% |
| **Stretch** | 100–250 points above | Developmental challenge. Forces the lower-rated player to adapt to higher-level play | 25% |
| **Anchor** | 100–250 points below | The inverse of a stretch match — the higher-rated player faces a stretch opponent. Builds confidence and reinforces fundamentals | 25% |

Every stretch match is simultaneously an anchor match for the opponent: when a 1000-rated player stretches up to face a 1200-rated player, the 1200-rated player is anchoring down. No separate scheduling is needed — one fixture serves both purposes.

---

## Daily Session Model

### Academy Training Context

Matches happen during daily academy training sessions:

| Parameter | Typical Value |
|----------|---------------|
| Session duration | 2–3 hours (150 minutes usable) |
| Tables available | 4–8 |
| Players present | 15–25 |
| Match format | Best-of-3 (training) or Best-of-5 (league day) |
| Average match duration | 15–20 min (best-of-3) or 25–30 min (best-of-5) |
| Changeover time | 5 minutes |

---

### Session Capacity Calculation

$$
\text{matches\_per\_table} = \left\lfloor \frac{\text{session\_minutes}}{\text{match\_duration} + \text{changeover}} \right\rfloor
$$

$$
\text{total\_match\_slots} = \text{matches\_per\_table} \times \text{num\_tables}
$$

$$
\text{matches\_per\_player} = \min\left(4,\ \left\lfloor \frac{\text{total\_match\_slots} \times 2}{\text{num\_present\_players}} \right\rfloor \right)
$$

---

**Example**: 150-minute session, 5 tables, 20 players, best-of-3 (20 min + 5 min changeover):

- Matches per table:  
  $$\lfloor 150 / 25 \rfloor = 6$$

- Total match slots:  
  $$6 \times 5 = 30$$

- Matches per player:  
  $$\min(4, \lfloor 30 \times 2 / 20 \rfloor) = \min(4, 3) = 3$$

Each player plays **3 matches** in this session.

---

## Daily Match Allocation

For a standard 3-match session:

| Round | Type | Purpose |
|------|------|---------|
| Round 1 | Competitive | Peer-level, closest rating |
| Round 2 | Stretch / Anchor | Developmental — lower-rated plays up, higher-rated plays down |
| Round 3 | Competitive | Peer-level, different opponent from Round 1 |

---

For a 4-match session the pattern depends on tier composition:

**Variety Maximization — C-S-C-S** (all tier groups have even player counts):

| Round | Type | Purpose |
|------|------|---------|
| Round 1 | Competitive | Peer-level |
| Round 2 | Stretch / Anchor | Developmental |
| Round 3 | Competitive | Peer-level, different opponent |
| Round 4 | Stretch / Anchor | Second developmental pairing |

Used when: every tier group present has an even number of players (e.g. 2, 4, 6). Even-sized groups are fully paired in a single competitive round, so alternating provides maximum match variety.

---

**Rotation Completion — C-C-S-C** (at least one tier group has an odd player count):

| Round | Type | Purpose |
|------|------|---------|
| Round 1 | Competitive (shift 0) | Peer-level |
| Round 2 | Competitive (shift 1) | Peer-level, cross-half pairing |
| Round 3 | Stretch / Anchor | Developmental |
| Round 4 | Competitive (shift 2) | Peer-level, third rotation |

Used when: at least one tier group has an odd number of players (e.g. 3 or 5). A 3-player tier needs 3 competitive shifts (0, 1, 2) to complete its internal round-robin — all three pairs appear once each. The C-S-C-S pattern only delivers 2 competitive rounds, guaranteeing one intra-tier pair is never scheduled. C-C-S-C fulfils the 3-round requirement while still providing a stretch round.

---

Both patterns maintain approximately the 50/25/25 split: 2 competitive + 1 stretch in a 3-match session, or 3 + 1 / 2 + 2 in a 4-match session.

